Answer 2¶

Failure rate quality checks of manufactured items --> 5% Success rate quality checks of manufactred items --> (100%-5%)= 95%

Sample size = 10

Binomial assumptions..-

  1. Number of trials are fixed,
  2. Only two possible outcomes in all the trials.
  3. Each trials are independent of each other
  4. Probability of success of each trial is fixed

Hence, this is classic case of binomial distribution

In [4]:
k=np.arange(0,11)
n= 10 # sample size
p = .05 # 5% failure rate ~ .05
In [5]:
binomial=stats.binom.pmf(k,n,p)
binomial

       1.58642578e-09, 1.85546875e-11, 9.76562500e-14])

Answer 3¶

Average car sales of a salesman per week --> 3

This is a poisson distribution, given lambda = 3.

Answer 4¶

Recognition accuracy of the bot --> 86.8%. Hence, failure to recognize orders correctly is (100%-86.8%) or 13.2%

This is again binomial distribution question as below assumptions holding true..-

  1. Number of trials are fixed,
  2. Only two possible outcomes in all the trials.
  3. Each trials are independent of each other
  4. Probability of success of each trial is fixed
In [17]:
k=np.arange(0,10)
n=3  # no. of trials
p = .132  #probability of not recognizing the order correctly
In [18]:
binomial2=stats.binom.pmf(k=np.arange(0,10),n=3,p=.132)
binomial2

Answer 4¶

Answer 4A¶

From above figures for Operating and Closed companies, it's evident that there's not much difference between data for Operating and Closed companies. However, in order to find the differences we will run Hypothesis test. Also, distribution is not exactly normal but since sample sizes > 30, we will assume Central Limit Theorem to hold good here and we will proceed ahead with z-test and t-test.

Answer 4B¶

For the test..-

Null Hypothesis: There is no difference between two means

Alternate Hypothesis: There is significant difference between two means

Answer 4C¶

In [216]:
from statsmodels.stats.weightstats import ztest

sample_1=data.loc[data['OperatingState']=='Operating','Funds_in_million']
sample_2=data.loc[data.OperatingState=='Closed','Funds_in_million']

test_statistic, p_value=ztest(sample_1,sample_2)

alpha_significance=.05 # Taking Confidence interval 95%

if p_value <= alpha_significance:
    print(f'Since p_value < alpha_significance, hence we Reject Null hypothesis')
    
else:
    print(f'Since p_value {round(p_value,4)} > {alpha_significance} (alpha), hence we Fail to reject Null Hypothesis and this means there is NO significant difference')

#test_statistic,p-value

Since p_value 0.255 > 0.05 (alpha), hence we Fail to reject Null Hypothesis and this means there is NO significant difference

In [217]:
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind

test_statistic, p_value= ttest_ind(sample_1,sample_2)

aplha_significance=.05 # Taking confidence interval .05

if p_value<alpha_significance:
    print(f'Since p_value {p_value} < {alpha_significance} (alpha), hence we reject Null hypothesis and this means there is difference')

else:
    print(f'Since p_value {p_value} > {alpha_significance} (alpha), hence we fail to reject Null Hypothesis and this means there is NO difference')
    
    

Since p_value 0.25572701885629406 > 0.05 (alpha), hence we fail to reject Null Hypothesis and this means there is NO difference
  • From above Hypothesis tests, we can conclude that more Funding does not lead to more success or vice versa

Answer 4H

In [239]:
from statsmodels.stats.proportion import proportions_ztest

test_statistic, p_value = proportions_ztest([contestants_operating, winners_operating], [contestants, winners])

alpha = .05

if p_value <= alpha:
    print(f'Since the p-value, {round(p_value, 4)} < {alpha} (alpha) the difference is significant and we reject the Null hypothesis')
else:
    print(f'Since the p-value, {round(p_value,4)} > {alpha} (alpha) the difference is not significant and, we fail to reject the Null hypothesis')

Since the p-value, 0.0374 < 0.05 (alpha) the difference is significant and we reject the Null hypothesis
